Case study: How does a bike-share navigate speedy success?¶

As a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team of Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago, the director of marketing believes that the company's future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships and with that being the case, our team was tasked to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently.

From these insights, our team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members.

However, the executives must first approve of our recommendations. In which, must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

Case information¶

Characters and teams¶

  • Cyclistic: A bike-share program that features more than 5,800 bicycles and 600 docking stations. Cyclistic sets itself apart by also offering reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making bike-share more inclusive to people with disabilities and riders who cant use a standard two-wheeled bike. The majority of riders opt for traditional bikes; about 8% of riders use the assistive options. Cyclistic users are more likely to ride for leisure, but about 30% use them to commute to work each day.
  • Lily Moreno: The director of marketing and your manager. Moreno is responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-share program. These may include email, social media, and other channels.
  • Cyclistic marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts who are responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Cyclistic marketing strategy. You joined this team six months ago and have been busy learning about Cyclistics mission and business goals as well as how you, as a junior data analyst, can help Cyclistic achieve them.
  • Cyclistic executive team: : The notoriously detail-oriented executive team will decide whether to approve the recommended marketing program.

About the company¶

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime.

Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members

Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Execution¶

1. Defining the problem¶

Company background¶

Cyclistic is a bike share company that offers short-term bicycle rentals to customers in the city of Chicago. They have a fleet of bicycles that are stationed at various docking stations across the city. Customers can rent the bicycles for a specified period and return them to any docking station in the city.

Cyclistic differentiates itself from its competitors by providing a premium experience to its customers. They offer two types of memberships: casual pass and annual membership. The casual pass allows customers to rent a bicycle for a single ride, while the annual membership provides unlimited rides for a flat fee.

To sustain and grow its business, Cyclistic needs to understand its customer base, identify usage patterns, and optimize its operations. This case study aims to address the following problem statement:

Problem statement¶

Cyclistic wants to understand how customers' usage patterns differ between the casual pass and annual membership holders. By analyzing the data, they seek to identify trends and patterns that can help them make strategic business decisions to increase the number of annual members and enhance the overall customer experience.

The specific objectives of the problem statement are as follows:

  • Differentiation of Usage Patterns: Determine the differences in usage patterns between casual pass users and annual members. Identify peak usage times, popular docking stations, trip durations, and other relevant factors that influence customers' preferences.
  • User Segmentation: Segment the customer base based on usage patterns, demographics, or any other relevant factors. Understand the characteristics and needs of different customer segments to tailor marketing efforts and improve customer targeting.
  • Promotion Optimization: Analyze the effectiveness of current promotional strategies for converting casual pass users into annual members. Identify opportunities for improving the conversion rate and recommend targeted promotions to attract more annual members.
  • Operational Efficiency: Identify operational inefficiencies or bottlenecks, such as bike availability, docking station capacity, or maintenance issues, that may impact customer experience. Propose solutions to improve operational efficiency and ensure a seamless bike sharing experience for customers.
  • Revenue Generation: Explore opportunities to increase revenue by optimizing pricing strategies, introducing new services or membership tiers, or forming partnerships with other businesses in the transportation or tourism industry.

Stakeholders goals and expectations¶

Stakeholder Goals Expectations
Lily Moreno Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. Data-driven, accurate, and reliable insights and analysis from the marketing analytics team

2. Data preparation and storing information¶

Data source and organization¶

The data used for the case study on Cyclistic is sourced from https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html. Made available by Motivate International Inc. under this license The dataset contains historical data on bike rides. In which, contains the columns:

  • ride_id: A unique identifier for each bike ride.
  • rideable_type: The type of bike for which what the user used for the bike ride.
  • started_at: The timestamp indicating the start time of the ride.
  • ended_at: The timestamp indicating the end time of the ride.
  • start_station_name: The name or location description of the docking station where the ride started.
  • start_station_id: The unique identifier of the docking station where the ride started.
  • end_station_name: The name or location description of the docking station where the ride ended.
  • end_station_id: The unique identifier of the docking station where the ride ended.
  • start_lat: The latitude coordinate of the docking station where the ride started.
  • start_lng: The longitude coordinate of the docking station where the ride started.
  • end_lat: The latitude coordinate of the docking station where the ride ended.
  • end_lng: The longitude coordinate of the docking station where the ride ended.
  • member_casual: The type of user, indicating whether the customer is a casual pass user or an annual member.

# Making a list of the numeric values of months in the yearmonth prefix of dataset filenames
# e.g. for year 2022 month of january, 202201-divvy-tripdata.csv
filename_record_prefix_2022 = list(6:12)
filename_record_prefix_2023 = list(1:5)

# Making a function to merge datasets by year and month range
merge_data_by_year_and_month_range <- function(year, filename_record_prefix) {
    # Initializing df as null for binding
    df <- NULL
    
    for (filename_prefix in filename_record_prefix){
        formatted_filename_prefix <- sprintf("%02d", filename_prefix)
        df <- rbind(df, read_csv(glue::glue("data/csv/raw/{year}{formatted_filename_prefix}-divvy-tripdata.csv")))
    }

    # Returning the merged data
    return(df)
}

df <- rbind(
    merge_data_by_year_and_month_range(2022, filename_record_prefix_2022), 
    merge_data_by_year_and_month_range(2023, filename_record_prefix_2023)
)

# Casting data as tibble
df <- as_tibble(df)

Data credibility with ROCCC¶

ROCCC process in identifying good data. The more high quality data we have, the more confidence we have in our decisions. | Factor | Assessment | | ------------- | ---------- | | Reliable | Only 77% of the dataset are complete prior to data preparation. 85% of the dataset are complete after data preparation. | | Original | The dataset is directly obtained by a first party group, Motivate International Inc. | | Comprehensive | The dataset is comprehensive in capturing relevant information enough to answer the business questions. | | Current | With the time frame of year 2022 months june-december to year 2023 months january-may, the dataset includes the most recent and relevant data to provide accurate insights and thus, gives an up-to-date view. | | Cited | As the dataset is sourced from reputable internal records and databases maintained by the company, it implies a level of reliability and accountability. |

The bike trip data columns provide valuable information on ride durations, start and end times, station locations, bike usage, and user types. This data enables analysis of customer preferences, identification of popular stations, and exploration of usage patterns. The dataset serves as a crucial resource for deriving insights and making data-driven recommendations to optimize Cyclistic's operations and enhance the overall customer experience.

Making a function to plot the dataset completeness composition

In [ ]:
plot_dataset_composition <- function(df_observation_group_completeness, title) {
    options(repr.plot.width=20, repr.plot.height=4)

    ggplot(data = df_observation_group_completeness, mapping = aes(x = "", y = value, fill = observation_group_label)) +
        geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
        labs(title = paste("\n", glue::glue("{title}"), "\n\n")) +
        coord_flip() +
        geom_text(aes(x = 1, y = (total_count_observations - total_count_incomplete_data) / 2, label = plot_label[1]), color = "white", size = 7) +
        geom_text(aes(x = 1, y = (total_count_observations - (total_count_incomplete_data / 2)), label = plot_label[2]) , color = "white", size = 7) +
        scale_fill_manual(values = c("#00caad", "#240e23"), breaks = c("Complete", "Incomplete")) +
        theme_void(base_size = 17) + 
        theme(
            plot.margin = margin(1,1,1.8,1.9, "cm"), legend.position = c(0.07,1.2), 
            legend.title = element_blank(), legend.direction = "horizontal")
}

# Making a function to get season from numeric representation of a month
get_season <- function(datetime) {
    month_numeric <- month(datetime)

    if (month_numeric %in% c(3:5)){
        return("Spring")
    } else if (month_numeric %in% c(6:8)) {
        return("Summer")
    } else if (month_numeric %in% c(9:11)) {
        return("Autumn")
    } else {
        return("Winter")
    }
}

get_distance_traveled_meters <- function(observation) {
    longitude_1 <- observation[2]
    latitude_1 <- observation[1]
    longitude_2 <- observation[4]
    latitude_2 <- observation[3]

    distance_in_meters <- round(pluck(distm(
        c(longitude_1, latitude_1), 
        c(longitude_2, latitude_2)),
    1), 2)

    distance_in_meters
}

get_mode <- function(df) {
    mode <- df %>%
        table() %>%
        as_tibble() %>%
        arrange(desc(n)) %>%
        pluck(1, 1) %>%
        as.double()

    return(mode)
}

Determining the popular docking stations across all user groups

In [ ]:
plot_popular_station <- function(x, y, title) {
    options(repr.plot.width=20, repr.plot.height=7)

    ggplot(mapping = aes(y = fct_reorder(y, x), x = x, fill = y)) +
        geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
        labs(title = paste("\n", glue::glue("{title}") ,"\n")) +
        geom_text(aes(label = x, hjust = -0.5), size = 4.3) +
        scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, direction = 1, option = "mako", alpha = 1) +
        theme_minimal(base_size = 17) +
        theme(
            plot.margin = margin(1,3,1.8,1.9, "cm"), 
            axis.title.y = element_blank(),
            axis.title.x = element_blank())
}

Key findings: Trends, relationships, and the inconclusive findings¶

Trends and relationships

  • Across all user groups
    • Bike trip peaks during saturday at ~750k and dips the following day at ~650k
    • Bike trips are scarce during the winter season
    • Most of the bike use composes of bike use with a duration of 5 mins and averages at 16 mins
    • Most of the distance traveled from start station to end station composes of trips with a distance traveled of 0 meters and averages at 2098.9 meters
  • Casual pass
    • Composes 39% of the June of 2022 to May of 2023 bike trip population
    • Bike trip count peaks at ~192k during the saturdays of summer
    • Most bike use have a duration of 7 mins and averages at 21.8 mins
    • Most bike use have a distance traveled from start station to end station of 0 meters and averages at 2124.9 meters
    • Where they start are spread out of the whole chicago
  • Annual member
    • Composes 61% of the June of 2022 to May of 2023 bike trip population
    • Makes up 35% of the classic bike usage and 25% for electric bikes
    • Does not use docked bike at all
    • Bike trip count peaks at ~178k during the wendesdays of summer
    • Most bike use have a duration of 4.8 mins and averages at 12.2 mins
    • Most bike use have a distance traveled from start station to end station of 0 meters and averages at 2082 meters
    • Mostly starts at stations at the chicago downtown area and upper lakeside

Inconclusive findings and speculations

  • Members get more out of the service by using it to commute consistently based on the factors that members:
    • Are particularly more active during wednesdays and thursdays
    • Bike usage dips after friday
    • Shows to have a dense amount of observations focusing around the downtown area where most of them start on
